work song piece music closely connected form work either sung while conducting task usually coordinate timing song linked task which might connected narrative description protest song Records work songs are old historical records and anthropological evidence suggests that most agrarian societies tend have them Most modern commentators work songs have included both songs sung while working well songs about work since the two categories are seen interconnected Norm Cohen divided collected work songs into domestic agricultural pastoral sea shanties African American work songs songs and chants direction and street cries Ted Gioia further divided agricultural and pastoral songs into hunting cultivation and herding songs and highlighted the industrial protoindustrial songs cloth workers see Waulking song factory workers seamen lumberjacks cowboys and miners also added prisoner songs and modern work songs societies without mechanical time keeping songs mobilisation calling members community together for collective task were extremely important Both hunting and the keeping livestock tended involve small groups individuals usually boys and young men away from the centres settlement and with long hours pass result these activities have tended produce long narrative songs often sung individually which might dwell the themes pastoral activity animals designed pass the time the tedium work Hunting songs like those the Mbuti the Congo often incorporated distinctive whistles and yodels that hunters could identity each others locations and those their prey Most agricultural work songs were rhythmic cappella songs intended increase productivity while reducing feelings boredom Rhythms work songs similar African drum beat served synchronize physical movement groups coordinating sowing hoeing and harvesting The usage verses work songs were sometimes improvised and sung differently each time Improvisation provided singers with subversive form expression Slaves sang improvised verses mock their overseers express frustrations and share dreams escaping Many work songs served create connection and familiarity between workers Yankee Doodle thought have started out harvest song its words possibly originating from farmers 15th century Holland contained mostly nonsensical and outofplace words that were presumably sang similarif not the sametune Yanker didel doodle down Diddle dudel lanther Yanke viver voover vown Botermilk und tanther Farm laborers Holland the time received their wages much buttermilk Botermilk they could drink and tenth tanther the grain AfricanAmerican work songs originally developed the era captivity between the seventeenth and nineteenth centuries Because they were part almost entirely oral culture they had fixed form and only began recorded the era slavery came end after 1865 Slave Songs the United States was the first collection AfricanAmerican slave songs was published 1867 William Francis Allen Charles Pickard Ware and Lucy McKim Garrison Though this text included many songs enslaved people other texts have also been published that include work songs Many songs sung enslaved individuals have their origins African song traditions and may have been sung remind the Africans home while others were instituted the captors raise morale and keep Africans working rhythm They have also been seen means withstanding hardship and expressing anger and frustration through creativity covert verbal opposition Similarly work songs have been used form rebellion and resistance Specifically AfricanAmerican Women Work Songs have particular history and center around resistance and selfcare Work songs helped pass down information about the lived experience enslaved people their communities and families common feature African American songs was the callandresponse format where leader would sing verse verses and the others would respond with chorus This came from African traditions agricultural work song and found its way into the spirituals that developed once Africans bondage began convert Christianity and from there both gospel music and the blues The call and response format showcases the ways which work songs foster dialogue The importance dialogue illuminated many African American traditions and continues the present day Particular the African call and response tradition the overlapping the call and response The leaders part might overlap with the response thus creating unique collaborative sound Similarly AfricanAmerican folk and traditional music focuses polyphony rather than melody with harmony Often times there will multiple rhythmic patterns used the same song resulting counterpoint rhythms The focus polyphony also allows for improvisation component that crucial AfricanAmerican work songs scholar Tilford Brooks writes improvisation utilized extensively Black folk songs and essential element especially songs that employ the callandresponse pattern Brooks also notes that often times work song the leader has license improvise the melody their call while the response usually repeats its basic melody line without change Also evident were field hollers shouts and moans which may have been originally designed for different bands individuals locate each other and narrative songs that used folk tales and folk motifs often making use homemade instruments early African captivity drums were used provide rhythm but they were banned later years because the fear that Africans would use them communicate rebellion nevertheless Africans managed generate percussion and percussive sounds using other instruments their own bodies Perhaps surprisingly there are very few examples work songs linked cotton picking Corn however was very common subject work songs typical plantation Because the crop was the main component most Africans dietcitation needed they would often sing about regardless whether was being harvested Often communities the south would hold cornshucking jubilees during which entire community planters would gather on