ailors between the eighteenth and twentieth centuries are known sea shanties These songs were typically performed while adjusting the rigging raising anchor and other tasks where men would need pull rhythm These songs usually have very punctuated rhythm precisely for this reason along with callandanswer format Well before the nineteenth century sea songs were common rowing vessels Such songs were also very rhythmic order keep the rowers together Because many cultures used slaves row some these songs might also considered slave songs Improvised verses sung sailors spoke ills with work conditions and captains These songs were performed with and without the aid drum Western music was directly influenced the folk music traditions immigrants the nineteenth century they moved west They reflected the realities the range and ranch houses where the music originated played major part combating the loneliness and boredom that characterised cowboy life and western life general Such songs were often accompanied mobile instruments guitars fiddles concertina and harmonica the nineteenth century cowboy bands developed and cowboy songs began collected and published from the early twentieth century with books like John Lomaxs Cowboy Songs and Other Frontier Ballads 1910 cowboys were romanticised the midtwentieth century they became extremely popular and played part the development country and western music Industrial folk song emerged Britain the eighteenth century workers took the forms music with which they were familiar including ballads and agricultural work songs and adapted them their new experiences and circumstances Unlike agricultural work songs was often unnecessary use music synchronise actions between workers the pace would increasingly determined water steam chemical and eventually electric power and frequently impossible because the noise early industry result industrial folk songs tended descriptive work circumstances political nature making them amongst the earliest protest songs and were sung between work shifts leisure hours rather than during work This pattern can seen textile production mining and eventually steel shipbuilding rail working and other industries other nations industrialised their folk song underwent similar process change can seen for example France where SaintSimon noted the rise Chansons Industriale among cloth workers the early nineteenth century and the USA where industrialisation expanded rapidly after the Civil War Lloyd defined the industrial work song the kind vernacular songs made workers themselves directly out their own experiences expressing their own interest and aspirations Lloyd also pointed various types song including chants labour love and erotic occupational songs and industrial protest songs which included narratives disasters particularly among miners laments for conditions well overtly political strike ballads also noted the existence songs about heroic and mythical figures industrial work like the coal miners the Big Hewer Big Isaac Lewis This tendency was even more marked early American industrial songs where representative heroes like Casey Jones and John Henry were eulogised blues ballads from the nineteenth century Industrial folk songs were largely ignored early folk song collectors but gained attention the second folk revival the twentieth century being noted and recorded figures such George Korson Pete Seeger and Woody Guthrie the USA and Lloyd and Ewan MacColl and Peggy Seeger Britain The genre declined popularity with new forms music and deindustrialisation the twentieth century but has continued influence performers like Billy Bragg and Bruce Springsteen 